column40: just doesn't seem like an ai wrote it
column53: has to end on a positive note
column66: doesn't seem to match the prompt too well
column105: doesn't have lots of really flowery words
column118: uses uncommon vocabulary but has a unique story structure
column157: seems similar in structure to another short story i read earlier and has a summary paragraph at the end

column79: did not adhere closely to prompt

column119: I thought the story was really engaging and I would've liked to read more if I could. The writing of this story signaled something human to me because of how the vampire's feelings were conveyed. You could tell that he yearned to know what the sun was like but couldn't due to his nature. It felt as if this story had to be written by a human.
column158: I have trouble believing this was written by a human because I'm not understanding how the alien forms a connection with the two humans they met. I also don't see how helping these people was a part of the alien's mission because all they do is feed on dreams. The story doesn't delve enough into the connection between the characters so there's a lack of emotional connection I have with the story and leads me towards the story feeling more like it was written by AI.
column170: The text was very closely related to aspects of the real world that I resonant with on an emotional level. It detailed some of the most unfortunate parts of our world and the use of repetition is almost like how a poem is written. It is a literary device typically used to emphasize a key point. Thus, I'm very inclined to believe that this was written by a human.

column23: it was actually kind of funny the descriptions of the penguins with the sundaes
column32: i feel quite drawn to the main character and his charisma
column36: I laughed out loud when the demon started raging about the coal being a diamond
column53: although I believe it was very likely LLM, this story also seemed slightly more authentic than the other LLM stories.
column58: the daughter blushing at being found out about the locket
column66: everything is too rushed and the responses to the ludicrous situations are implausible--humans would not react in such ways.
column105: I'm pretty sure LLM's don't cuss.
column106: There's quite a few formatting and grammar issues in this story.
column127: Sticky the imaginary friend was very creepy
column129: great ambiguity especially with the sticky character and Tod's suggested insanity
column158: The ending of this one is still machine like, but at least it's written with a greater sense of beauty
